<TEXT>
a judge tuesday issued a restraining order 
barring an alderman who threatened to disrupt the citys annual 
great circus parade from coming within 500 feet of the parade route 
alderman michael mcgee censured last month by his colleagues 
for threatening violence if inner city problems arent dealt with 
warned monday that he and members of his black panther militia 
planned to disrupt the parade mcgree wrote to parade organizer ben 
barkin that parents should keep their children at home because the 
protest could get ugly he indicated the city had no right to 
enjoy itself while its black community was convulsed with violence 
and poverty 
the city responded tuesday by obtaining the restraining order 
from milwaukee county circuit judge john e mccormick 
the memo to ben barkin in my opinion was a threat of 
violence city attorney grant langley said 
the parade annually attracts 500000 people or more who line the 
twomile route through the downtown area it features restored 
antique circus wagons marching bands equestrienne groups clowns 
and other attractions 
we are very concerned about the potential for disruption 
having an effect on the animals frightening the animals langley 
said noting that mcgees unspecified disruption could involve 
anything from mass whistleblowing to tossing fireworks 
langley said the temporary restraining order applies to mcgee 
and five others named in the order as well as all other members of 
mcgees black panther militia and anyone else acting in concert 
with the alderman 
mcgee censured by the common council two weeks ago was 
unavailable when the associated press attempted to reach him at his 
city hall office and at his home for comment there was no answer 
at those telephone numbers 
doris green one of those named with mcgee in the restraining 
order read a statement at a news conference in which mcgeen said 
it would be an honor to be arrested while protesting at the parade 
mcgee has repeatedly criticized the city for failing to address 
inner city problems he formed the militia earlier this year and 
claims it has 500 members including street gang members who will 
take violent action if inner city problems arent eased by 1995 
the common council censured mcgee june 29 after he announced he 
had received a sausagepoisoning threat from a militant group 
causing a local company to recall thousands of dollars worth of 
meat products 
city officials claimed that mcgee invented the poisoning threat 
</TEXT>
