<TEXT>
an infectious strain of hepatitis that can 
cause several liver diseases is spread even more rapidly than aids 
among gay men according to a study announced tuesday 
the hepatitis b virus is contracted 86 times more easily than 
the human immunodeficiency virus that causes aids according to a 
university of pittsburgh study published in the journal of the 
american medical association 
since the beginning of the aids epidemic hepatitis b has been 
pushed in the background said dr lawrence kingsley who led the 
study of 1062 gay men in pennsylvania ohio and west virginia 
the virus infects an estimated 300000 more americans every 
year and 5 to 10 percent of them will develop cirrhosis liver 
cancer or chronic liver disease the centers for disease control in 
atlanta reported 
studies from the early 1980s have shown 50 to 70 percent of gay 
men carry the hepatitis b virus researchers said 
other disease researchers said the pitt study is significant 
because it dramatically shows that the hepatitis b strain is passed 
much more easily than the aids virus through sexual contact and 
exchange of body fluids 
the viruses are linked in their similar patterns of spread 
both by blood and both by sexual contact said dr joseph melnick 
of baylor university in houston 
dr rebecca van dyke of the university of michigan said the 
comparison of the two viruses proves what long was suspected by 
doctors who have treated gay men in the 1980s 
i worked in san francisco and we had hepatitis b all over the 
place and we knew it was transmitted fairly quickly ms van 
dyke said 
she said the emergence of aids has made more people aware of all 
sexually transmitted diseases including hepatitis b but at the 
same time those at risk of getting aids may not pay attention to 
other diseases and seek treatment 
the b strain is the only one of five types of hepatitis that can 
be prevented with a vaccine researchers said about 25 million 
americans received it in 1989 and most of them were healthcare 
workers said the cdcs dr miriam alter the vaccine was developed 
by researchers who studied gay men in new york city because the 
strain was so prevalent among homosexuals ms van dyke said 
the pitt study also said anal intercourse puts men at a high 
risk for contracting hepatitis b other studies have claimed higher 
aids infection rates are linked to anal intercourse 
because hepatitis b is so easily transmitted were trying to 
underscore the need for safer sex the use of condoms kingsley 
said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

