<TEXT>
both the democrats and the republicans 
are underdogs in the connecticut governors race this year voters 
seem smitten with the thirdparty campaign of a maverick exsenator 
they ousted from office just 1 years ago 
lowell p weicker jr narrowly lost his bid for a fourth senate 
term in 1988 but roared back onto the states political scene in 
march forsaking the gop and declaring his candidacy as an 
independent 
poll after poll has found weicker to be the frontrunner in the 
gubernatorial race far ahead of the two congressmen who are 
expected to claim the republican and democratic nominations 
but weicker who created his own party the connecticut party 
discounts the polls he remembers 1988 when he was favored for 
reelection to the senate and lost by 10000 votes to democrat 
joseph lieberman 
g donald ferree jr director of polling at the university of 
connecticut said weicker is riding almost 20 years of statewide 
support but he predicts the race will tighten as the candidates 
stake out positions and become better known 
because voters arent hearing much and because weicker has 
such a strong advantage in terms of familiarity theres been very 
little movement ferree said it would be a mistake to interpret 
the current numbers as hardened preferences he said 
this is the first time in 20 years that connecticut democrats 
arent favored to win the governors office the party is 
foundering after democratic gov william a oneill was forced to 
raise taxes by more than 1 billion last year 
oneill citing political realities and saying he had no 
stomach for a nasty campaign in march dropped plans to run for 
reelection 
the democratic frontrunner now is fourterm rep bruce a 
morrison who was challenging oneill for the nomination the day 
oneill dropped out littleknown state rep william j cibes jr 
announced he was jumping in 
morrison is expected to receive the partys endorsement at the 
nominating convention this weekend but cibes appears assured of 
getting the 20 percent of convention delegates needed to force a 
september primary 
many oneill democrats have been cool to morrison because of his 
challenge to the incumbent democrat oneill himself remains openly 
resentful questioning morrisons ability to win and refusing even 
to meet with him 
republicans who have won the governors office just once in 35 
years had thought 1990 would be their year the party saw oneill 
as vulnerable on tax and budget issues and believed morrison would 
be an easy target too because of his liberal voting record in 
congress 
in their own candidate threeterm rep john g rowland the gop 
saw a brash young congressman who had won in a democratic district 
and looked like the right new face rowland is poised to accept his 
partys nomination by acclamation at its july 2021 convention 
what the gop didnt count on though was weickers candidacy 
