<TEXT>
special agents armed with stopwatches instead 
of guns are trying to clean up the city 
the eight agents hit the streets monday in a new effort to clear 
the air by enforcing a 1972 law against car bus and truck drivers 
who leave engines idling for more than three minutes 
its part of mayor david dinkins plan to let new yorkers 
breathe easier 
nothing else that we can do will bring us an improvement in 
our air quality faster than obtaining general citywide compliance 
with the threeminute idling law dinkins said 
department of environmental protection spokeswoman tina casey 
said eight tickets were issued on the first day including four at 
the jacob javits convention center all eight went to buses she 
said 
needless to say were thrilled at the small number of tickets 
that we had to issue she said they must have gotten the 
message 
around noon monday at a parking lot crowded with buses near the 
convention center a group of drivers said they werent happy with 
the citys enforcement plans 
its like an oven in there said terrence mcintosh a driver 
for short line of mahwah nj pointing to his bus with the 
temperature near 90 he said his passengers were not going to be 
happy to get into a hot bus 
the drivers also complained that the fines which they not 
their employer would have to pay were too high 
first offenders will get a ticket for 220 and the fines can go 
up as high as 880 for repeat offenders 
thats just a little less than what we make said cruz 
quintana another short line driver his company pays about 360 a 
week to starting drivers he said 
transportation commissioner lucius j riccio called the 
penalties commensurate with the violation 
we mean business riccio said 
riccio said that if the operator of a ticketed vehicle is not 
the owner then the owner also is subject to a fine 
were talking about the air that we breathe and the 
environmental and health impacts of that riccio said if 
people want to be selfish and leave their vehicles running then 
that means that other people suffer 
the law does not apply to vehicles that need the engine to 
operate some equipment such as a truck mixing concrete 
richard mendes deputy dep commissioner said more than 200 
summonses have been issued annually in the past for idling 
violations 
