<TEXT>
president violeta barrios de chamorro 
called out the army monday night to quell protests by thousands of 
sandinistas who have blocked streets with barricades and fought 
her supporters with guns fists and rocks 
gunfire could be heard in many parts of the nicaraguan capital 
but reporters could get not close because of the shooting 
police sources who insisted on anonymity said at least three 
people were killed and more than 100 injured in the unrest which 
began sunday night 
mrs chamorro addressed the nation on state radio and television 
as thousands of sandinistas backing a weeklong wave of strikes 
returned to the streets and defying government orders erected 
more barricades 
there was some question however of whether the 
sandinistadominated army would support mrs chamorro 
in the speech the president urged democratic nicaraguans not 
to let themselves be provoked and not to answer violence with 
violence which has already claimed victims 
the speech was delayed for four hours as police cleared 
prosandinista students and workers who had seized a government 
broadcasting center 
mrs chamorro who took office in april after handing the 
sandinistas a stunning electoral defeat said her government was 
committed to national reconciliation that ought to occur in a 
climate of peace and understanding not of fear and intimidation 
nicaraguas economy has been battered by nearly 10 years of war 
between the sandinistas and the now disbanded usbacked contra 
rebels and by an economic embargo by the reagan administration 
mrs chamorro accused the leftist sandinistas of directing the 
nationwide strike and inciting unrest despite their defeat in 
february elections at the hands of her usbacked coalition the 
sandinistas remain the countrys largest political force 
the strikes which have plunged nicaragua into chaos were 
called in part to protest what unions say are massive firings by 
the chamorro government workers also want a greater voice in 
setting economic policy 
daniel ortega who mrs chamorro unseated as president urged 
her government to negotiate 
this conflict cannot be solved by force any attempt in that 
direction is an invitation to chaos he said in a radio interview 
the road to the international airport was blocked monday night 
by barricades made of paving stones police using backhoes had 
cleared debris earlier but the strikers blocked the road again 
the demonstrators burned rubber tires and trash alongside the 
barricades monday night sending smoke billowing over the city 
it was reminiscent of the 1979 revolution when sandinistas 
