<TEXT>
the environmental group 
greenpeace marked the fifth anniversary of frances sabotage 
sinking of its protest ship rainbow warrior by presenting gruyere 
cheese to the french embassy today 
to the beat of a drum the 18 protesters also delivered to the 
embassy a wreath a mock grave and a headstone marked f pereira 
murdered july 1985 
french secret agents blasted two holes in the hull of the 
rainbow warrior a 30yearold former north sea cod trawler as it 
was moored in auckland harbor just before midnight on july 10 
1985 dutch photographer fernando pereira 33 drowned as he tried 
to save his camera gear 
greenpeace nuclear testban spokeswoman stephanie mills said the 
gruyere cheese was symbolic of mururoa atoll the site of french 
nuclear testing in the pacific she said the atoll is full of holes 
and acts as a leaky radioactive waste dump 
france has conducted 60 atmospheric nuclear tests over mururoa 
and more than 120 underground tests since 1975 four have been held 
in the last month another two are expected soon 
six days after the rainbow warrior sinking police arrested two 
of the bombers maj alain mafart and capt dominique prieur of 
the french secret service which wanted to stop greenpeaces 
antinuclear protests 
two months later thenfrench prime minister laurent fabius 
confirmed that secret service agents were responsible defense 
minister charles hernu resigned and the secret service chief adm 
pierre lacoste was sacked 
mafart and prieur pleaded guilty to manslaughter charges and 
were sentenced to 10 years in jail chief justice sir ronald 
davison called the destruction of the rainbow warrior a 
deliberate planned action of a terrorist nature 
un secretarygeneral javier perez de cuellar agreed in june 
1986 to mediate the international dispute over the incident 
he ruled that france should apologize and pay new zealand 7 
million as compensation he also said mafart and preiur should be 
transferred to hao atoll a french military facility on an isolated 
island outside europe for three years on july 23 1986 they were 
handed over to the french who moved them to hao 
in december 1987 mafart returned to paris without new zealands 
consent the french claimed he needed medical attention for stomach 
pains thennew zealand prime minister david lange called the move 
an outrage 
in early may 1988 just before the french presidential election 
prieur was whisked back to france again without new zealands 
consent amid reports she was pregnant 
new zealand filed a formal complaint to france over the agents 
repatriation and asked unsuccessfully that they be returned to 
hao 
two months ago a threeperson international tribunal ruled that 
france had breached terms of the 1986 settlement france agreed to 
a suggestion that it set up a 2 million frenchnew zealand 
friendship fund 
