<TEXT>
many temporary census workers may be 
ineligible for unemployment compensation when their jobs end 
because of a change in the law 
the actual number of people affected is hard to estimate because 
rules for unemployment compensation eligibility vary from state to 
state neither congressional or census spokesmen would estimate the 
number affected 
in the past temporary census jobs have counted toward 
eligibility for unemployment compensation just as any other job 
however this year an appropriations bill signed by president 
bush on may 25 set an april 20 cutoff on census workers getting 
credit toward unemployment temporary census work done after that 
date doesnt count when they are eventually laid off and apply for 
unemployment benefits 
how that cutoff affects individual workers depends on the 
unemployment eligibility rules in their states some states for 
example require 26 weeks of work before someone becomes eligible 
people who havent accumulated that before april 20 would not be 
able to collect benefits 
