said because walker flew too close to an airliner near washington 
dc in 1988 
air force col frederick d gregory will replace walker as crew 
commander on the shuttle flight 
at his news conference monday lenoir said nasa engineers plan a 
fullscale leak test on atlantis on friday or saturday the test 
will be performed while the space shuttle sits on the launch pad 
and will closely duplicate the conditions that resulted in both the 
columbia leak in may and the leak found on atlantis in june 
after the second leak nasa halted space shuttle launches until 
the problem is fixed 
the rockwell test over the weekend used plumbing hardware called 
an umbilical that had been taken from columbia after its leak was 
found engineers forced liquid hydrogen through the umbilical and 
maintained a pressure of 50 pounds per square inch they then 
measured any hydrogen that leaked 
lenoir said the leak amounted to 5000 to 10000 cubic inches of 
hydrogen per minute the columbia leak in may had been about 90000 
cubic inches per minute 
a hole the size of a pinhole about 40000th of an inch would 
be large enough to create such a leak in the liquid hydrogen 
system he said 
for atlantis test engineers at the kennedy space center in 
florida stripped away insulation and exposed the bare metal of the 
umbilical they are installing special instruments and sensors and 
attaching plastic bags to areas of the pipe assembly that could be 
leaking 
when all is ready hydrogen chilled to a liquid at minus 423 
degrees will be pumped through the pipes at the rate of more than 
80 gallons a minute 
by analyzing gas captured by the bags and readings on the 
sensors the experts hope to find the exact location of the leak 
lenoir said the prime suspect for the source of the leak is 
a ushaped teflon seal that is supposed to keep hydrogen from 
escaping from the disconnect joint 
he said the tolerances for the seal and for the groove that 
holds it are extremely tight and there could be just enough of a 
misfit to cause a leak 
if this is confirmed as the problem lenoir said there is a 
possibility it could be fixed in time for atlantis to fly in august 
but robert crippen director of the space shuttle program said 
engineers still have not pinpointed the leak source 
we really do not know what the problem is yet he said at 
the news conference with lenoir we havent eliminated anything 
yet 
while the leak test on atlantis may give answers crippen warned 
that it could also raise more questions 
we have not eliminated the possibility that we might have two 
different problems on the two different vehicles he said 
</TEXT>
