<TEXT>
from a friendly class photo to a highminded 
declaration on world peace and prosperity public shows of harmony 
come easy to the economic summit partners but major items on the 
agenda set each apart from the others 
that goes double for the united states this time president bush 
stands in the minority in arguing against western aid to the soviet 
union and hes greatly outnumbered in refusing to set new goals 
for cutting global pollution 
but that didnt shrink bushs smile as he and his six summit 
partners marched shouldertoshoulder through an extravagant 
ceremony monday 
harmony after all is a chief priority of these summits 
after some choreographed posing for news cameras the leaders 
disappeared into a rice university hall for two hours of formal 
talks then it was back before the cameras this time for the 
traditional group photograph and some lighthearted banter 
it was clear before the houston summit began that bush would not 
be converted to the majority view on providing emergency financial 
aid to moscow so the real challenge behind the scenes was to find 
a way to move the issue down the diplomatic road to leave it for 
later when the publicity stakes were lower 
the us position on aid to moscow illustrates how on some 
issues each summit country has special reasons for marching to a 
different drummer bush says the american public wont accept 
giving money to moscow until gorbachev ends soviet support for 
cuba a communist nation that is a political thorn in the american 
side but of relatively little concern to most of the other summit 
countries 
on the key environmental issue at the summit how to respond to 
the threat of global warming caused by polluting industrial plants 
bush worries that european and canadian ideas on cutting 
pollution could damage the us economy 
perhaps the most telling case of national interest concerns 
japan on the one hand it is alone among the participating 
countries in wanting to resume lending to china the others in 
houston say china has not moved far enough toward democratic 
reform and yet japan is staunchly against aiding the soviet union 
agreeing with bush that its better to wait for more democratic 
reforms 
history explains why japan takes what appear on the surface to 
be contradictory stances while the japanese have a tradition of 
close business ties to china they are still bitter that josef 
stalin seized the kurile islands from them after tokyo was defeated 
in world war ii 
taizo watanabe the japanese foreign ministry spokesman said 
tokyo has a unique perspective on china and that this special 
experience explains why it wants to resume lending despite the 
chinese crackdown last year on a prodemocracy movement 
we know more than anyone about what is going on there said 
watanabe 
france too travels a lonely path on at least one summit issue 
it wants the rich western governments to forgive more of the 
foreign debt of the worlds poorest nations the us position 
accepted by most of its summit partners is to consider debt relief 
only on a casebycase basis 
for west germany aid to the soviet union is the issue that sets 
it apart from the united states and several other nations in 
houston together with its push for more ambitious goals in cutting 
global pollution 
the germans face a unique political challenge in trying to win 
soviet acceptance of nato membership for a reunified german nation 
the bonn government has decided to do this by encouraging a huge 
western aid program for moscow and by extending generous loans on 
its own 
as with most tough issues put on the economic summit agenda 
these problems wont be fully resolved in houston but if past 
practice holds the leaders will find a way to keep their 
differences from spoiling their show of unity 
