<TEXT>
an asteroid sped past earth at a 
comparatively tiny distance of 3 million miles today scientists 
said 
the asteroid estimated at 300 feet to 1000 feet in diameter 
made one of the closest crossings of earth orbit observed in 50 
years the jet propulsion laboratory said 
the rocky object dubbed 1990 mf was located on june 26 by jpl 
planetary scientist eleanor helin at palomar observatory 
helin heads the palomar planetcrossing asteroid survey a 
project to systematically search for asteroids crossing near earth 
the asteroid was 8 million miles from earth and traveling 
approximately 12500 mph when spotted it was then tracked last 
week by arecibo observatory in puerto rico and by the national 
aeronautics and space administrations deep space network at 
goldstone calif 
initial calculations indicate the asteroid has an elongated 
orbit of 161 million miles and takes two years and four months to 
complete each orbit 
scientists continued to track it from siding spring australia 
mount john observatory new zealand the infrared telescope 
facility at mauna kea hawaii and harvard observing station at oak 
ridge mass 
the asteroid brightened and accelerated as it approached earth 
it was expected to surpass 22000 mph at closest approach 
the jpl sky survey team has found 39 nearearth asteroids since 
beginning the program in 1973 
</TEXT>
