<DOCNO> AP900710-0095 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
western leaders today welcomed the political and 
economic change that has swept eastern europe and urged romania to 
join its neighbors in adopting reforms 
europe is at the dawn of a new era president bush and 
leaders of six other rich democracies said in their final political 
communique 
we welcome enthusiastically the profound and historic changes 
sweeping the european continent the leaders said on the second 
day of their annual economic summit 
they said they will use every opportunity to push for a united 
and free europe and expressed pleasure at the impending merger of 
the two german states which they said would offer a major 
contribution to stability 
they urged romania where there has been violent repression of 
antigovernment demonstrators to join in the positive trend 
under way in neighboring countries 
the western nations already have promised billions of dollars in 
loans food and other assistance to moscows oncestaunch allies in 
eastern europe but they are still undecided about what to do for 
the soviet union 
their decision could be crucial for soviet president mikhail 
gorbachev who is trying to save his embattled economic reform 
program of perestroika 
a year ago at their summit in paris the leaders tapped the 
european community the 12nation trading bloc to find ways to 
help poland and hungary which were just beginning to revamp their 
backward economies 
since then the community has scrambled to bring together 
twodozen western countries and drum up commitments of more than 
12 billion in a variety of aid for poland and hungary 
the assistance is making a major contribution to reviving 
the stricken economies of poland and hungary said the community in 
a report on the yearlong program 
it has underpinned a radical stabilization program in poland 
which might otherwise have proved too risky and helped both 
countries to begin modernizing their economies it said 
because of the riches promised by the program other nations in 
eastern europe have appealed for help 
last week the foreign ministers of the group of 24 the 
western nations taking part in the program admitted 
czechoslovakia bulgaria east germany and yugoslavia romania was 
temporarily refused membership because of the recent violent 
repression of antigovernment demonstrators there 
no specific sums were promised to the new members but their 
addition to the program will likely mean billions of dollars in 
help 
to gain admittance the emerging democracies must commit 
themselves to the rule of law respect for human rights introduce 
multiparty political systems hold free and fair elections and 
impose economic reforms 
leaders in central and eastern europe who seek radical change 
in their countries political and economic systems accept the 
conditionality attaching to western assistance as a spur to 
reform said the communitys report 
it is also a guarantee to their peoples that the international 
community is paying close attention to the respect for political 
and economic freedom in their countries it said 
in setting conditions western officials hope to avoid pouring 
money into the economies only to have it squandered they contend 
loans granted to poland in the 1970s were wasted because of a 
poorly functioning economy poland now is having problems paying 
back its foreign debt of about 40 billion 
east european officials say the toughest part of their work is 
changing their centrally planned economies into the freemarket 
models practiced in the west 
to do that the countries must start from scratch 
they have to phase out government subsidies to farmers and 
others stabilize prices strengthen their virtually worthless 
currencies and allow private citizens to own property 
they also must create banking systems and develop labor markets 
complete with social security measures 
these are welcome indeed indispensable changes but they may 
well create transitional problems said the communitys report 
the soviet union could try to buy more goods from western 
nations rather than its neighbors in the east it said 
a further contraction in trade among the east europeans could 
exacerbate economic difficulties just as the reform process enters 
a critical phase the report said 
such drastic changes will likely cause at least temporarily 
higher unemployment and falling living standards 
the removal of subsidies and of guaranteed lifetime employment 
will test the social fabric and the libertarian values of the 
peoples involved the report said 
the western nations want their money to be used to overcome some 
of these obstacles 
</TEXT>
