<TEXT>
two plumbing fixtures were installed on the 
space shuttles despite failing initial tests for leaks sen al 
gore dtenn said today they were among seven such fixtures that 
did not pass tests he said 
gore said the hydrogen plumbing fixtures called umbilicals 
were tested with liquid nitrogen using a simulated spacecraft part 
on one side when the units failed the test they were retested in 
another way he said 
nasa spaceflight director william lenoir denied that the parts 
failed the test he said retesting in a different manner was a 
normal part of the procedure 
lenoir said the umbilicals were first tested against what isunit which 
simulates where the umbilicals would 
called a slave be 
attached to the space shuttle orbiter 
the slave unit is not flight hardware therefore it is more 
likely to be the source of a leak than is the flight hardware 
said lenoir 
he denied that the test was redesigned in order to assure that 
the umbilicals would pass 
when leaks were detected in the first test lenoir said the 
slave unit was removed and a blank plate was substituted this was 
done he said because it was assumed the leak was from the rnings were 
2000 or 30 an hour after expenses 
that compares to the 7 an hour from the legitimate jobs that 75 
percent of the probationers reported holding 
we came to this study from an employment perspective said 
karen hastie williams chairwoman of the committee on strategies to 
reduce chronic poverty one of the groups that commissioned the 
study 
we hoped to identify employment and training strategies to 
convince drug dealers to end their involvement in the underground 
economy and join the legitimate work force 
but conceded economist peter reuter even creation of 
considerably higher paying legitimate jobs probably wouldnt get us 
very far dealers would still have smaller total incomes than they 
can earn now by supplementing their regular wages with drug 
selling also many of them have expensive drug habits 
reuter the reports principal author said in an interview 
that while most streetlevel sales were by blacks the 
availability of drugs in washington affects not just the citys 
predominantly black population 
our figures show that there are 79000 cocaine addicts in the 
washington metropolitan area and over 78 percent of them live in 
suburban areas he said therefore a lot of people who are 
involved in drug transactions may not be black but are suburban 
whites who come into the city to make purchases and who take the 
drugs back to their communities for sale or use 
while a typical city street dealers earnings arent enough to 
finance flashy cars and lavish lifestyles it is the image of such 
luxuries that draw many young men into selling drugs reuter said 
in an interview 
people such as rayful edmond iii a convicted city cocaine 
kingpin send the wrong messages to many people who are considering 
getting involved in selling drugs they see that people like 
edmond who was able to create a large illegal drug organization 
living what they believe to be a high lifestyle but they never 
see the downside the consequences that can result from such 
activity 
edmond on trial on a murder charge has already been sentenced 
to life in prison without parole on a string of drug convictions 
the study found that dealers active at least two days a week 
face a 22 percent chance of going to prison a 7 percent chance of 
severe injury and a 14 percent chance of being killed a fatality 
rate 100 times that of the general work force 
given those risks the report said long periods of steady 
earnings are unlikely to be common 
looking at black men born in 1967 the study found that up to 
one in six had been charged with selling drugs by the time he 
turned 20 for the future the researchers said the ratio is 
likely to be closer to one in three before that age group reaches 
30 
the study held out some hope among the youngest group surveyed 
the 387 ninth and tenth graders while one in six was selling 
drugs only about 11 percent were using them 
that could mean that antidrug messages may be getting through 
to the younger population in the city reuter said adding 
however the downside is that many juvenile sellers are involved 
in other delinquencyrelated offenses 
