<TEXT>
a 95yearold man who is believed to be the 
oldest murder defendant in city history is back in the apartment 
building where he allegedly bludgeoned a neighbor to death 
the slaying of 88yearold norma marks has tenants at the 
building on manhattans upper west side demanding the immediate 
jailing of oliver barre he was arrested after being found covered 
with blood on the floor of the dead womans apartment on june 16 
authorities said 
barre told police he beat mrs marks to death with a metal pipe 
in selfdefense he was released without bail by two judges over 
the protests of residents and the prosecution 
i was quite concerned to have a person in that condition 
walking around the building said cyla guerwicz a 23year 
resident he could snap at any moment its a reasonable 
concern 
more than 140 residents signed a petition demanding barre go to 
jail pending his trial the petition said they feared for their 
collective safety and wellbeing 
barre a navy officer during world war i was released on his 
own recognizance by criminal court judge laura drager who also 
turned down prosecution requests that he be held for psychiatric 
tests 
another judge ordered barre to hire a roundtheclock home 
attendant to keep an eye on him 
barre told a police officer who responded to the slaying that 
mrs marks was a murderer who had poisoned 15 to 20 people in the 
building court documents indicated 
barre who had minor scratches claimed mrs marks had tried to 
strangle him and she was killed in selfdefense the document said 
mrs marks was struck repeatedly with a metal pipe suffering a 
fractured skull jaw and ribs along with massive cuts and bruises 
two officials of the prosecutors office dismissed barres 
defense as well as a published report that the killing was 
prompted by a love triangle involving a third woman age 86 the 
officials spoke on condition of anonymity because the case is 
before a grand jury 
the manhattan district attorneys office says it knows of no one 
older than barre ever charged with murder in the city 
assistant district attorney bridget brennan told acting state 
supreme court justice george roberts on tuesday that the grand jury 
could decide on an indictment by the end of the week 
barre who appears solidly built attended the brief court 
session in a wheelchair wearing a baseball cap that read us 
submarine veterans he sat silently as brennan addressed the 
judge 
defense attorney john bb lewis assisted by a nurse pushed 
his client out of the courtroom and into an elevator without 
commenting on the case the attorney also did not return a phone 
call to his office 
