<TEXT>
manuel noriegas longtime personal banker and 
five codefendants formed a partnership in crime to launder 32 
million in drug profits through worldwide financial transactions a 
prosecutor said tuesday 
the defendants five bank of credit and commerce international 
employees plus a colombian airplane broker knew the huge sums of 
cash they were trying to disguise were proceeds of cocaine sales 
but didnt care assistant us attorney mark jackowski said in 
closing arguments 
in fact they even offered helpful laundering hints to an 
undercover agent to skirt ladea which stood for the drug 
enforcement administration he said 
from the evidence there should be no doubt in anyones mind 
the funds that were picked up on the streets of this country were 
from the sale of cocaine jackowski told the jury in summing up 
the governments case in the sixmonth trial 
a us customs agent posing as a wellconnected highstakes 
launderer during a twoyear sting told the bankers his clients were 
dope dealers who dont like mistakes jackowski said 
drugs smuggled into the united states were sold on the streets 
and the cash was converted into certificates of deposit that first 
were used as collateral for loans then to pay them off as they 
matured the government maintained 
the drug profits hidden through these elaborate transactions 
involving bcci subsidaries in panama luxembourg france and 
switzerland eventually were to wind up back in the hands of drug 
dealers to finance the next haul according to prosecutors 
what the government must prove is that the defendants acted in 
bad faith and that they didnt do so by some kind of mistakes 
or accident the prosecutor told jurors what it really is is a 
partnership in crime 
charged with conspiring to launder drug profits for the medellin 
cartel and with various laundering counts are five officers of the 
luxembourgbased bcci including amjad awan banker for deposed 
panamanian leader noriega 
on trial with awan who was miamibased assistant director of 
bccis latin american division are askbar a bilgrami a director 
of bccis latin american division syed aftab hussain bccis 
operations officer of the bank in panama sibte hassan an officer 
in the paris branch ian howard french country manager based in 
paris and rudolf armbrect of medellin colombia 
the bankers claim they never intentionally violated the law and 
were entrapped by the undercover agent 
the six defendants face a possible penalty of five years on the 
conspiracy count plus 20 years on each of the 30 laundering 
charges all are charged with conspiracy and various combinations 
of laundering 
