<TEXT>
liberian rebel leader charles taylor 
said tuesday his forces will refuse to observe a ceasefire and 
predicted he would capture the city of monrovia by the end of the 
week 
taylor speaking in a telephone interview with the british 
broadcasting corp was responding to published reports that he had 
accepted a ceasefire and the rebels march on the capital was 
suspended 
there will be no ceasefire taylor said 
taylor whose men appear to have made little progress since 
reaching the outskirts of monrovia a week ago said his national 
patriotic front is progressing carefully because of the massive 
loss of life 
we are only proceeding with caution while we evacuate people 
into safety zones to receive food and medical treatment he 
said this is why we have not stormed the capital as we should 
he conceded the final assault was taking a long time saying 
i understand that and i regret the long time but if we were to 
move in and tear that city apart the whole world would be jumping 
all over us 
he added my troops are exchanging fire right now in monrovia 
i think that monrovia should be down by the weekend 
the french news agency agence france presse which has a 
reporter with the rebels reported tuesday that the insurgents were 
executing members of president samuel does krahn tribe and members 
of the mandingo people accused of supporting doe 
a pool report filed by correspondents in the besieged liberian 
capital said government troops continued to kill suspected rebel 
supporters a 19yearold man was bundled into a car and taken to a 
beach where soldiers slit his throat the report said 
the sixmonth conflict which began with taylors invasion from 
ivory coast on dec 24 has become a tribal war does forces were 
accused of killing hundreds of civilians from the gio and mano 
tribes the main rebel support base the rebels have accused does 
administration of being corrupt 
taylor said the rebels were sending a delegation to peace talks 
in freetown sierra leone to hear what mediators from the economic 
community of west african states are proposing 
the talks were scheduled to open tuesday but the rebel 
delegation failed to arrive probably because of transport problems 
the economic community group reportedly has proposed 
introduction of a multinational african peacekeeping force in 
liberia to oversee new elections taylor has opposed that 
there will be no foreign soldiers landing on one inch of 
liberian soil taylor said he said some members of the economic 
community mediation team were supporting doe and had sent him 
weapons 
doe meanwhile reportedly has agreed to resign but only after 
a stable interim government is set up 
liberian information minister emmanuel bowier in freetown for 
the mediation talks said doe had no intention of being driven out 
of monrovia by the rebels but would step down in favor of a 
national unity government the government would have to include all 
sides in the conflict bowier said 
the plan reportedly also rules out taylor heading the 
transitional government the rebel said there will be no interim 
government that is not headed by charles taylor 
the rebels have refused to accept a ceasefire until doe resigns 
and leaves the west african nation 
