<TEXT>
a coalition of consumer health and insurance 
groups said tuesday that more federal leadership and money are 
needed to help prevent 600000 deaths that result each year from 
consumer products 
in releasing a status report the coalition for consumer health 
amp safety said 80 percent or more than 480000 of those deaths 
involved cigarettes and alcohol 
stephen brobeck chairman of the coalition said that while 
there are hopeful trends many improvements are needed 
particularly discouraging is the recent rise in motor vehicle 
and household product deaths and the two most dangerous products 
cigarettes and alcohol still take a horrendous toll he said 
federal agencies must increase their efforts in all of these 
product areas to do so they must be adequately funded said 
brobeck executive director of the consumer federation of america 
which formed the coalition 
brobeck did not say how much money should be added to the effort 
overall but with respect to the consumer product safety 
commission he said its 35 million budget for this year should be 
increased to 75 million 
politically that wont happen but it should he said 
more money also needs to be channeled to the national highway 
traffic safety administration and to combat aids and alcoholism 
brobeck said but he did not specify how much 
the report focused on seven areas of concern motor vehicle 
safety home and product safety cigarette smoking indoor air 
pollution food safety and nutrition alcohol consumption and aids 
among the findings 
47093 people were killed in motor vehicle accidents in 1988 
an increase of 15 percent from 1987 when 46390 died on the 
nations roadways and a 06 percent rise from the previous years 
toll of 46087 
falls were the leading cause of fatal accidents in the home 
accounting for 6500 deaths in 1988 fires were the secondranked 
cause followed by suffocation poisoning firearms and drownings 
cardiovascular disease one of the key factors for which is 
diet killed nearly 1 million americans in 1987 while nutritional 
deficiencies caused a reported 2890 deaths in the united states 
that year 
cigarette smoking was responsible for 390000 deaths in the 
united states in 1985 between 1965 and 1987 the proportion of 
american adults who smoked dropped by 40 percent for men and 21 
percent for women about 49 million americans still smoke 
cigarettes 
alcohol was involved in 90991 deaths in 1986 up from 88935 
the previous year 
the coalition of 37 groups includes 16 insurance companies and 
associations as well as health groups such as the american academy 
of pediatrics and the american college of preventive medicine and 
consumer groups like the center for science in the public interest 
