<DOCNO> AP900710-0124 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
textron lycoming agreed tuesday to pay the 
government 179 million to settle a fraud investigation focusing 
on the companys problemplagued coast guard helicopter engines 
the settlement is the largest ever reached under the justice 
departments whistleblower lawsuit program 
robert c ballew a procurement official for the prime 
manufacturer of the coast guard hh65a dolphin helicopters will 
receive 27 million for his role in filing the original suit 
against textron in may 1988 
textron based in stratford conn was under investigation for 
providing engines that failed to meet their operating 
specifications and for fraudulently billing the coast guard for 
repair work according to the justice department the helicopters 
are used in searchandrescue and drug interdiction missions 
former coast guard commandant paul yost once referred to the 
engine as a lemon 
separate investigations by the national transportation safety 
board have shown according to published reports that at least 14 
deaths are attributable to failures of the lts101 engine 
manufactured by textrons lycoming williamsport pa plant the 
engine is used in private helicopters as well as air ambulances 
commercial choppers and air national guard helicopters 
this settlement sends a clear message that the government will 
simply not tolerate fraud perpetrated against the american 
taxpayer said stuart gerson assistant attorney general for the 
justice departments civil division 
textron also agreed to maintain the engines and supply parts for 
the next six years and be paid a fee based on the engine flying 
time that provision could save the coast guard an estimated 60 
million according to the justice department 
this arrangement will increase textron lycomings incentive to 
improve the engines longevity since textron lycoming will now 
bear the costs of the replacement parts gerson said 
the twoyear government investigation showed that the engines 
were operating at higher temperatures than was called for in their 
initial design as a result the engines were deteriorating faster 
than expected the engine was supposed to fly for 2400 hours 
between overhauls it usually lasted less than 600 hours before 
expensive repairs were required 
the probe also turned up evidence that textron charged the coast 
guard for work related to repairing engine defects even though the 
coast guard had stated it would not pay the charges 
textron issued a written statement that admitted no wrongdoing 
but the company said it hoped to normalize relations with the coast 
guard and pledged to maintain the reliability and mission 
availability of the engines 
textron said it had set aside money for the settlement and that 
the 179 million payment will have no material impact on the 
companys bottom line 
ballew 43 of fort worth texas worked for aerospatiale 
helicopter corp a french firm that makes the dolphin he said in 
a telephone interview that he filed the suit because he feared he 
could be sent to jail when aerospatiale was unable to cure problems 
with the engines supplied by textron 
under a civil warera law whistleblowers can sue on behalf of 
the government and are entitled to a portion of any settlement 
ballews share amounts to 15 percent of the total 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

