western leaders paid tribute tuesday to east 
europeans who have overthrown repressive regimes to bring about 
political and economic changes on their continent they urged 
troubled romania to follow the example of its neighbors 
president bush and the leaders of six other rich democracies 
attending their annual economic summit hailed the moves in central 
and eastern europe toward democratically elected governments and 
freemarket economies 
europe is at the dawn of a new era they said in a political 
statement we welcome enthusiastically the profound and historic 
changes sweeping the continent 
they said they wanted to seize all opportunities to achieve a 
europe whole and free and welcomed the drive toward unification 
of the two german states the german merger they said should 
contribute to stability in europe 
the leaders called on romania to adhere to the positive 
trend unfolding in neighboring countries the bucharest 
government has been accused of complicity in the recent violent 
repression of antigovernment protestors 
they said they were ready to give fledgling democracies needed 
constitutional legal and economic advice and financial assistance 
as appropriate 
the leaders remarks underscored their efforts to aid the 
countries in eastern europe as they pull away from the soviet 
union long their main support 
at last years summit in paris bush and his counterparts asked 
the european community the 12nation trading bloc to fashion an 
aid program to encourage the changes unfolding in poland and 
hungary 
in just a year twodozen wealthy nations including the united 
states france west germany and japan have promised to give more 
than 12 billion in loans technical advice and food supplies to 
poland and hungary 
reacting to appeals from other east european countries they 
agreed last week to draw czechoslovakia east germany bulgaria and 
yugoslavia into the program romania was temporarily denied 
membership because of the political repression there 
its not known how much the west will be able to raise for the 
four new additions to the aid program but help will likely be 
substantial 
in a report on the program the communitys executive body said 
the assistance is making a major contribution in helping the 
sick economies of poland and hungary 
it has underpinned a radical stabilization program in poland 
which might otherwise have proved too risky and helped both 
countries to begin modernizing their economies it said 
in handing out the aid the western nations insist that the new 
democracies commit themselves to the rule of law respect for human 
rights introduce multiparty political systems hold free and fair 
elections and impose economic reforms 
leaders in central and eastern europe who seek radical change 
in their countries political and economic systems accept the 
conditionality attaching to western assistance as a spur to 
reform said the community report 
it is also a guarantee to their peoples that the international 
community is paying close attention to the respect for political 
and economic freedom in their countries it said 
the money is designed to help east european officials change 
their outdated economies from centrally planned ones to freemarket 
systems 
to do that the governments must build from the ground up 
they need to get rid of government subsidies to farmers and 
others stabilize prices and bolster worthless currencies they 
must develop banking systems and labor markets 
the community said in its report that the changes are 
indispensable but may well lead at least temporarily to higher 
unemployment and reduced living standards 
