<TEXT>
a government official said tuesday that 
colombia will never allow us troops to conduct antidrug 
operations on its territory saying such rambotype actions 
were better suited for american cities 
foreign minister julio londono made his remarks in a radio 
interview with the rcn network in response to an article in the 
july 16 issue of newsweek 
the newsweek article said the us southern command based in 
panama was drawing up contingency plans for us troops to play a 
support role in a dramatic series of antidrug strikes aimed at 
crippling the cocaine cartels in peru bolivia and colombia 
however the magazine said such raids were unlikely to happen 
anytime soon or possibly ever because of opposition in congress 
and the state departments reluctance to offend latin american 
countries 
colombian news media interpreted the newsweek article as 
suggesting us troops might be used in colombia 
but londono said colombia was opposed to any us military 
intervention and said washington could best assist in the drug war 
by helping the local economy 
where these rambotype actions are needed is in the big 
north american cities where big distribution centers are found and 
drugs are sold on street corners with the knowledge of american 
authorities londono told rcn 
if any us aid is needed it should be in the form of 
paying fair prices for our export products and avoiding import 
taxes on our agricultural and industrial products he added 
newsweek said the militarys contingency plans called for the 
forces of colombia peru and bolivia to attack local cartel 
targets while us forces would not be used in actual strikes all 
the logistics planning training and support would be provided by 
the americans the magazine said 
the magazine quoting an unidentified intelligence source said 
the pentagon has plans to use us special forces to capture 
colombian drug lords on orders from president bush 
colombia has a deeprooted sensitivity to a us military 
presence dating almost 90 years to the construction of the panama 
canal 
panama was long a part of colombia but in 1903 the united 
states backed a group of rebels who established a separate republic 
and signed a treaty for construction of the canal 
the us government has repeatedly demonstrated over the years 
that it understands colombias sensitivity about any us military 
role here 
last year president bush sent bogota 65 million worth of 
military aid for the antidrug war 
the us military transport planes flying in the equipment 
stayed only a few hours in bogota and the 150 american military 
technicians spent a few days in colombia to help set up the 
equipment and train troops in its use 
even so the colombian news media ran several stories about the 
presence of us troops in the country at the time 
