<TEXT>
a federal judge tuesday suspended part of a 
wisconsin experiment that cuts the welfare benefits of families 
whose children skip school ruling that recordkeeping errors have 
resulted in cruel treatment 
an recent audit of the program showed that some families were 
being wrongly penalized because of poorly kept school attendance 
records a lawsuit against the program said one family was evicted 
from its home and others had to turn to food pantries for food 
us district judge terence t evans ordered the suspension of 
learnfare in milwaukee public schools at least until an improved 
system of recording school absences in the states largest city was 
devised 
it is an experiment with worthy goals of attempting to reduce 
welfare dependency and provide incentives for children to stay in 
school evans wrote in his ruling but recipients of aid to 
families with dependent children should not be made homeless and 
hungry in the name of social experimentation he said 
evans granted a preliminary injunction requested by the advocacy 
group legal action of wisconsin on behalf of six milwaukee families 
whose afdc benefits were cut by learnfare 
the injunction applies only to the 3200 teenagers attending 
milwaukee public schools who have lost or are in danger of losing 
afdc benefits under learnfare state officials said the program 
would continue elsewhere in the state 
learnfare authorized by the legislature in 1987 allows the 
state to cut a familys monthly afdc benefits if a school reports a 
student has been consistently absent without excuse penalties 
average about 100 a month for an average family receiving 517 a 
month in benefits 
the program applies to teenagers but gov tommy g thompson 
has received permission from the federal government to expand it to 
include elementary school students 
thompson said late tuesday the injunction was not a judgement of 
the merits of learnfare but of administrative problems in 
milwaukees public schools 
theres no question learnfare is a good program its 
working he said whats wrong is some very poor record 
keeping im just happy the injunction was granted in the 
summertime 
the milwaukee lawsuit filed in december charged the program 
violates the social security act and the us constitution it 
named as defendants the state department of health and social 
services and the milwaukee county department of social services 
it cited problems with the administration of learnfare 
especially attendancekeeping procedures in the milwaukee public 
schools and the states appeals hearing process 
evans said he would lift the injunction if the state and 
milwaukee county remedy their problems with monitoring school 
absences 
legal action attorney patricia delessio said 1600 to 2000 
milwaukee students are sanctioned each month under the program 
she said evans injunction did not address all of the legal 
challenges of learnfare pending in the courts 
we focused on the immediate administrative problems which i 
would describe as glaring she said it means welfare benefits 
will not be cut any longer 
assembly speaker thomas loftus a democrat who is challenging 
thompson in this falls governors race predicted the injunction 
would put a halt to learnfare 
i think it will stop it dead in its tracks for the foreseeable 
future loftus said 
</TEXT>
