<TEXT>
dennis mcfarland knows a lot about quitting 
he studied music but gave it up stage fright then came 
writing novels hed stop cold at page 45 he even tried real 
estate hated it and left six months later 
wary of becoming legitimate he again took up writing but 
how long can a husband and father way past 21 tell people hes 
still finding himself still trying to get that first book 
published 
so when mcfarland started on a new novel centered on a man 
whose brother commits suicide the author decided this was one 
project he had to complete 
its sort of like youre doing something in the dark i 
believed in myself and my wife believed but it didnt seem that 
anybody else would be affected if i quit writing said mcfarland 
41 whose novel is called the music room houghton mifflin 
1995 
i had quit on everything else i always thought that something 
had happened to me in the middle but with this book i decided no 
matter what else happens i was going to keep on and rejection 
after rejection i kept on writing 
the music room begins with martin lambert learning that his 
25yearold brother perry has jumped from the window of a 
manhattan hotel room martin 29 flies in from san francisco to 
find out what happened falls in love with perrys old girlfriend 
jane owlcaster and discovers he knew little about his brothers 
life 
now on the surface this has little to do with mcfarland a 
native of mobile ala he never had a brother commit suicide he 
did not come from a musical family unlike the one in the novel 
nor were his parents alcoholics the room that gives the book its 
title is vividly described but also does not really exist 
but this is a story about quitting jobs marriages life 
itself martin like mcfarland has a history of unfinished 
business hes disconnected easily distracted when martin 
receives the call about his brothers death he puts the detective 
on hold moves the french windows that overlook his garden and 
watches a hummingbird dart outside 
later lying in bed next to perrys girlfriend martin thinks 
about the early deaths of his brother and father killed by 
alcoholism at age 42 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
when i closed my own eyes i thought at once of perry of how 
despite his drive to succeed despite his apparent selfpossession 
he had been in his own way lost and then i thought how surely 
the whole family was lost and father was lost to himself as he 
groped his way towards his absurd early death how often he would 
open the door to a room surprised to find us there oh im 
sorry boys i was looking for the a stray in his own 
home 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
another link between author and subject martin is in his late 
20s and realizes hes unhappy selling his san francisco record 
company to start a new life in new york mcfarland remembers his 
late 20s as a time when he hated his life hated getting up he 
had given up on music sharing martins distaste for a career of 
teaching ear training to a bunch of college students 
i realized that even i became one of the most successful 
people in the field composing or performing maybe theres 100 
people who would care said mcfarland who studied music at 
brooklyn college and now lives outside of boston 
it was so esoteric i decided i would like a larger audience 
if i was going to do something artistic 
martin drinking heavily accuses jane of hiding information 
about the suicide frightened aware that fullblown sorrow over 
his death still brewing at sea had not yet reached shore he 
escapes to his mothers house in norfolk va 
one day walking in the fields on a warm autumn afternoon he 
has a vision the kind of vision that is the brutal side of 
grief the vision of an impossible future 
he pictures a celebration a birthday party for his father its 
late summer and both parents are sober perry is alive and happy 
playing backgammon with his mother jane resting her hands on his 
shoulders their children are running by the water 
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
as the squeals of the children fleeing the cool surf and 
the laughter attending the backgammon game reach my ears thinks 
martin i am filled with the faith and quiet confidence that 
belongs to those who were given the heart and willingness to 
survive to those given the great fortune to have continued 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
imagine those words as something mcfarland said to himself at 
one of the many times he was ready to give up the novel and perhaps 
take another look at selling houses thats why the music room 
is a personal novel regardless of how different his life is from 
martins and thats why the author saw no other way to end the 
story than to make sure his character lived 
either you die or you start to go back up mcfarland 
observed i probably will never write the book where it ends with 
the person hitting bottom and staying there thats just not what i 
want my vision to be 
i believe that enormous grief and enormous loss are 
survivable thats the greatest story for me 
</TEXT>
