<TEXT>
prodded by british officials economic summit 
negotiators renewed efforts today to resolve differences over 
president bushs proposal to abolish billions of dollars in foreign 
farm subsidies 
us trade representative carla hills was meeting later in the 
day with frans andriessen the top trade negotiator for the 
european community to discuss ways to break their stalemate over 
the farm subsidy question 
afterwards aides to summit leaders were expected to meet late 
into the night in their search for a trade compromise to include in 
the final summit communique that will be issued wednesday 
british officials urged compromise britain is a member of the 
european community but doesnt have as big a stake in the subsidy 
issue because it has fewer and smaller farms than their summit 
partners 
british foreign secretary douglas hurd warned today that failure 
to reach agreement could be extremely damaging to longterm global 
prosperity 
this negotiation will not succeed unless we are all prepared 
to go for a compromise he said in a bbc interview 
while fights over the arcane language of trade agreements 
usually are left to subordinates to settle this dispute has 
attracted the attention of the leaders of seven major industrial 
democracies because of the huge stakes involved 
the bush administration believes that the united states best 
hope of resolving its 100 billion trade imbalance is to expand 
export opportunities for us farmers and businesses by 
liberalizing the rules governing world trade 
freer global trade also holds out the promise of providing an 
economic lifeline for struggling new democracies in eastern europe 
and latin america by expanding the markets for their goods 
but it is far from clear whether the trade talks known as the 
uruguay round for the country where they began in 1986 will 
succeed given entrenched positions in such areas as agriculture 
the talks are being conducted by the 97nation general agreement on 
tariffs and trade the world body that governs trade 
before coming to houston bush said that without fundamental 
reform in agriculture the united states would walk away from the 
uruguay round bush aides said monday that the president has been 
taking a tough line in houston in his discussions with summit 
colleagues 
the president has been doing a very good job to indicate why 
agriculture is the lynchpin to these negotiations ms hills said 
bush brought up the trade negotiations in a string of oneonone 
sessions with world leaders and then devoted a part of the first 
formal session monday to talking about agriculture 
bush is making the point very forcefully to his summit 
partners that this is an enormously important activity 
agriculture secretary clayton yeutter told reporters calling 
bushs discussions a motivating session to get the europeans 
engaged 
in discussions with jacques delores president of the european 
communitys executive body bush took a tough stance telling 
delors that the political leaders needed to exhibit political 
courage to resolve the issue an ec official said 
it was tough it was frank the official said speaking on 
condition of anonymity 
bush also discussed the farm dispute in separate meetings with 
french president francois mitterrand and west german chancellor 
helmut kohl the two european leaders with the strongest opposition 
to total elimination of farm subsidies 
kohl however indicated that in his discussions he believed a 
compromise proposal on the agricultural issue represented a good 
starting point to trying to resolve the issue 
the document drawn up by aart de zeeuw a former dutch official 
who is chairing the agricultural negotiations strikes a 
middleground between the defensive ec position and the aggressive 
us stance 
in the summits opening session kohl told the other leaders 
that there was a critical need to insure a successful conclusion of 
the trade talks being held under the auspices of the 97nation 
general agreement on tariffs and trade 
he told the leaders that the summit needed to give the 
negotiators a positive signal and a political orientation that 
we all jointly stand for strengthening the gatt 
yeutter said kohls stance was mildly encouraging with other 
officials suggesting that it could represent a breakthrough if 
other european nations follow west germanys lead 
hills told reporters that the united states hoped to achieve a 
commitment from the summit countries to use the de zeeuw paper as 
the basis for working out a final agreement on agriculture 
in addition to phasing out farm subsidies the united states has 
an ambitious goal of expanding global trade rules to include about 
1 trillion in trade not now covered by the gatt 
the us proposal would result in the elimination of barriers to 
trade in the highgrowth area of banking and other services where 
us companies are extremely competitive 
american negotiators are also pushing to extend gatt rules to 
cover better enforcement of trade and copyright piracy which is 
estimated to cost american companies 60 billion in lost sales each 
year 
agriculture is seen as the key to the whole us package because 
third world countries have balked at agreeing to the proposals on 
expanding gatt coverage unless they win expanded markets for their 
farm products 
