<DOCNO> AP900710-0230 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the state supreme court ruled that patients 
have no right to share in profits if their blood or organs become 
the source of lucrative scientific research 
in a major victory for the us biotechnology industry the 
court said that john moore a leukemia victim whose spleen was 
removed for medical reasons could not sue researchers and 
commercial laboratories on the claim that his personal property was 
being misused he did however win limited rights to sue on more 
narrow grounds 
the 52 decision monday said that researchers used the victims 
spleen without his knowledge to develop a blood protein with 
multibilliondollar medical potential 
allowing such a suit threatens to destroy the economic 
incentive to conduct important medical research said the opinion 
by justice edward panelli 
the multibilliondollar industry relies heavily on a plentiful 
supply of human cell lines thousands of which exist in tissue 
repositories throughout the country 
the court unanimously allowed moore of seattle to maintain his 
suit on a more limited basis a claim that the doctor who removed 
his spleen and later withdrew blood samples over several years had 
failed to disclose his personal interests before getting moores 
consent to the procedures 
that part of the ruling should encourage a more open 
doctorpatient relationship in the future said cynthia fruchtman 
a los angeles lawyer and expert in genetic engineering 
its going to facilitate a dialogue between participants in 
research and researchers themselves so that the public knows 
whats going on said fruchtman 
after moores suit was filed she said some research hospitals 
changed their consent forms to specify that tissues removed may be 
used in research 
if nothing else it allows the patient to ask questions about 
whats going on fruchtman said one of john moores 
complaints as i understand his suit was that he wasnt given that 
information and the opportunity to ask those questions 
the disadvantages to moore in such a suit are that he cannot sue 
the laboratories unless he can show that they were involved in the 
failure to disclose facts and that under normal legal rules he 
could recover damages only for whatever losses he suffered without 
sharing in any profits 
it would appear that a justifiable sigh of relief should go up 
from the scientific community said richard d godown president 
of the industrial biotechnology association a trade group of 107 
companies 
a defendant in the case sandoz pharmaceuticals corp had 
warned in papers filed with the court that the field of 
biomedical research will be plunged into a state of chaos for 
years if the court allowed a suit for conversion or use of 
moores property without his consent 
however moores lawyer sanford gage said the limited claim 
allowed by the court could still include a share of the profits 
a doctor who operated on moore without proper consent and 
companies that knowingly took part in nondisclosures over the 
following years could be required to disgorge illgotten 
gains gage said 
he said he considered the limited decision a victory because 
this allows us to proceed and it does protect patient rights 
moore was a 31yearold alaska pipeline surveyor in 1976 when he 
sought treatment for a type of leukemia called hairycell leukemia 
at the university of california los angeles dr david golde 
removed moores spleen a standard treatment and the disease has 
not recurred 
while testing the removed spleen golde discovered it contained 
unique blood cells that produced a blood protein called gmcsf 
which is now in experimental use as a drug to stimulate the immune 
system to fight certain cancers and possibly aids 
for nearly seven years moores suit said golde and others 
brought moore from seattle to los angeles for blood tests and other 
procedures never telling him of his cells value while they 
developed moores cells into a selfperpetuating cell line to 
massproduce gmcsf 
the regents of the university of california patented the cell 
line in 1984 naming golde and a research assistant shirley quan 
as the inventors the same year moore sued golde quan the uc 
regents and the two companies working on the product sandoz and 
genetics institute inc 
the suit estimated the potential value of the product as 3 
billion it said golde and others had gotten 3 million worth of 
genetics institute stock 
goldes lawyer donn dimichele said today that he was pleased 
that the court had rejected moores main claim but uncertain about 
the effect of the section that would allow suits for failure to 
disclose a researchers interests 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

