<TEXT>
martin marietta corp has sued the intelsat 
consortium over who will pay for the bungled launch of a 157 
million communications satellite 
in the lawsuit filed in us district court martin marrietta 
asks that it not be held liable for the fouled march 14 launch 
involving one of its titan rockets which was sent into a low 
useless orbit 
the company has accused the washingtonbased intelsat of making 
unlawfully coercive demands and says intelsat should be held 
responsible for the mishap 
the contract terms provided that intelsat clearly had the 
financial risk said philip giaramita a spokesman for bethesda 
mdbased martin marietta thats really the heart of the 
matter 
the suit filed friday says intelsat a satellite operating 
company had threatened on july 3 to sue if martin marietta did not 
pay damages for the launch intelsat is expected to argue that 
martin marietta was grossly negligent in conducting the launch 
intelsat spokesman tony trujillo said the consortium would 
comment only in its court reply to the chares which must be made 
within 60 days 
in 1987 martin marietta signed a 112 million contract to 
launch the satellite using a titan booster intelsat paid 
separately for the satellite 
satellite operators often take out commercial insurance against 
a failure but intelsat did not opting instead to set aside funds 
of its own to cover such a contingency 
the rocket lifted off routinely on march 14 but once it reached 
space it failed to separate from the satellite it was stranded in 
a low useless orbit 
intelsat is negotiating with the national aeronautics and space 
administration to have space shuttle astronauts attach a rocket to 
the satellite that would send it up to its proper orbit that would 
cost the company about 90 million 
martin marietta has blamed the failure on faulty electrical 
engineering in its titan booster but contends its financial 
responsibilities ended at liftoff the suit said the contract 
allowed intelsat to request a replacement launch at a stipulated 
price if the first one failed and it has not done so 
the suit said if martin marietta loses the lawsuit if may 
withdraw from the commercial space launch business 
