<TEXT>
a federal jury tuesday convicted usx 
corp and two united steelworkers officials of conspiring to give 
the union officials company pensions in exchange for approval of a 
key labor contract 
usx was convicted of all 14 counts of conspiracy violating 
federal labor law and mail fraud union district 36 director 
thermon phillips and subdirector eb rich each was convicted of 
one count of conspiracy and one count of violating federal labor 
law 
rich 60 was acquitted of 10 counts of mail fraud ten mail 
fraud charges against phillips 62 were dismissed earlier the 
verdict came on the 10th day of deliberations in us district 
court 
usx faces a maximum penalty of 41 million phillips and rich 
each face a maximum 10 years in prison and 500000 in fines at 
sentencing aug 20 
i think it shows the labor community that the public is not 
going to sit still for skulduggery theyre going to demand honest 
upright labor negotiations first assistant us attorney buddy 
kelly said 
usx said it would appeal the verdict to the 11th us circuit 
court of appeals in a statement the company maintained the 
charges were the products of strained and erroneous 
interpretations of complex statutes 
the government claimed at the 17week trial the union officials 
engaged in illegal negotiations in exchange for approval of a work 
contract that cut wages and benefits but allowed usxs fairfield 
works plant in birmingham to reopen 
the government alleged phillips and rich former steel company 
employees illegally negotiated pensions for themselves and four 
other union officials during talks in 1983 
the government said rich received a pension based on about 31 
years of work but only worked there 13 years phillips pension was 
based on about 38 years of employment but he worked for the company 
only from 194651 prosecutors alleged 
defense attorneys contended the pensions were not negotiated 
during the talks and the defendants did not try to conceal them 
they said rich and phillips never made pensions a condition of 
resolving the fairfield negotiations 
in 1984 usx then us steel changed its longstanding policy 
against giving pensions to former employees who became labor 
representatives the company paid more than 300000 in pensions to 
phillips rich and the other four union officers until the practice 
was halted in 1988 
union president lynn williams and the unions top lawyer 
testified that they read and filed a march 1985 us steel letter 
reporting the pension policy change and the granting of six 
pensions to unidentified union officers 
other union representatives testifying for the government said 
they did not learn of the change under which they may have been 
eligible for company pensions until 1987 
the union said in a statement it expected the charges against 
rich and phillips to be overturned on appeal based on numerous 
trial errors williams said the trial was more of an inquisition 
than a search for the truth 
</TEXT>
